I"!.<p>Performance. We hear about it often and talk about it plenty at developer conferences, but maybe we need to shift our focus to a different audience: designers. We already know that performance is a corner-stone to the success of our projects, and since <a href="https://www.keycdn.com/blog/web-performance-experts/">media is the bottleneck to performance optimization</a>, <strong>why aren‚Äôt we talking about it at design events?</strong> Why is performance typically not a priority in the design process? <em>99% of response time problems are still caused by the UI being too slow. <a href="https://blog.radware.com/applicationdelivery/applicationaccelerationoptimization/2014/01/55-web-performance-stats-youll-want-to-know/">[source]</a></em></p>

<p><strong>Performance optimization is a team effort</strong> and we need to get the whole team on board instead of waiting for the point in the project where we‚Äôre developing the thing to double-back and fix our mistakes. We need to start prioritizing performance (and accessibility) as a part of the design process, because it is. <a class="twitter-share">Performance is a design challenge.</a></p>

<h2 id="an-open-letter-to-digital-designers">An Open Letter to Digital Designers:</h2>

<p><br /></p>

<p><em>Dear Web Designer,</em> üíï</p>

<p><em>You have the power to make the Internet a faster, more accessible place. You can bring content to your users quickly and efficiently, and use load time efficiently. You affect the bottom line, right now, because performance is in your hands.</em></p>

<p><em>But it isn‚Äôt just about that bottom line. It‚Äôs about making an experience work seamlessly. It‚Äôs about saving humans from frustration, cognitive load, and the most valuable resources we have ‚Äî time and money. (Yes, money ‚Äî because <a href="https://speakerdeck.com/benschwarz/vanity-performance-metrics-looking-beyond-the-numbers">websites can be more expensive to access than you realize</a>).</em></p>

<p><em>You have such a big impact, and can literally make the web better for other humans. We need you!</em></p>

<p>üíñ <em>The People of the Internet</em></p>

<h2 id="win-1-image-optimization">Win #1: Image Optimization</h2>

<style>
#twitter-widget-0 {
  margin-right: auto;
  margin-left: auto;
  margin-bottom: 2em !important; /*override*/
  margin-top: 2em !important; /*override*/
  display: block;
  width: 100%
}
</style>

<blockquote class="twitter-tweet" data-lang="en"><p lang="en" dir="ltr">üò± During the last Olympics, the avg webpage was less than half the size it is today.<br /><br />üò¨ Images have also doubled. <a href="https://t.co/UshDN4KTb6">pic.twitter.com/UshDN4KTb6</a></p>&mdash; Una Kravets (@Una) <a href="https://twitter.com/Una/status/695062118719029248">February 4, 2016</a></blockquote>
<script async="" src="//platform.twitter.com/widgets.js" charset="utf-8"></script>

<p>And other than fonts, the latest update is even worse (Charts sourced from <a href="http://httparchive.org/interesting.php">HTTP Archive</a>):</p>

<p><img src="../images/posts/des-perf/july-update.jpg" alt="July Update" /></p>

<p>Images are the biggest ‚Äúbang for your buck‚Äù performance win because media assets take up the majority of web resources [see diagrams above]. There are a few things you can do to make sure that the assets you are putting online are performant.</p>

<blockquote>
  <p>Never put an image on the web that hasn‚Äôt been optimized ‚Äî <a href="https://twitter.com/davatron5000">Dave Rupert</a></p>
</blockquote>

<p>The first is to <strong>choose the correct image format</strong>. Some formats are more performant than others in different use cases, so this could get tricky. I.e. for an icon containing a limited color range (2-5 colors), an svg or png may be ideal. A photo with a wide range of color is more performant as a jpg. The best way to test an image is to ‚Äúsave for web‚Äù in a program such as Photoshop and try out various image formats and compressions. Once you‚Äôve determined the media format, <strong>compress it!</strong> And as a bonus, <strong>consider using a <a href="https://www.sitepoint.com/lazy-loading-images-not-really-annoy-users/">lazy loading</a> technique</strong> to improve UI load time.</p>

<p>For a general reference, here‚Äôs a great flowchart by (the really talented) <a href="https://twitter.com/sarah_edo">Sarah Drasner</a>:</p>

<p data-height="520" data-theme-id="light" data-slug-hash="VjvGJM" data-default-tab="result" data-user="sdras" data-embed-version="2" class="codepen">See the Pen <a href="http://codepen.io/sdras/pen/VjvGJM/">Animated Flow Chart to demo animating viewBox</a> by Sarah Drasner (<a href="http://codepen.io/sdras">@sdras</a>) on <a href="http://codepen.io">CodePen</a>.</p>
<script async="" src="//assets.codepen.io/assets/embed/ei.js"></script>

