<h3 id="image-optimization-mini-checklist">Image Optimization Mini-Checklist</h3>

<ul>
  <li><input type="checkbox" /><label>Resize images to fit their containers. <br /> <span class="small-check"><em>(Don‚Äôt send assets larger than the greatest common factor size)</em></span></label></li>
  <li><input type="checkbox" /><label>Download <a href="https://imageoptim.com">ImageOptim</a> and run your asset folder through it</label></li>
  <li><input type="checkbox" /><label>Remove additional layers and artifacts from SVGs <br /> <span class="small-check"><em>(such as uneccesary headers from Sketch or Illustrator)</em></span></label></li>
  <li><input type="checkbox" /><label>Minify SVG with <a href="https://jakearchibald.github.io/svgomg/">SVGO</a></label></li>
  <li><input type="checkbox" /><label>Consider using <a href="https://scottjehl.github.io/picturefill/">Picturefill</a> for retina images and responsive assets</label></li>
  <li><input type="checkbox" /><label>Lazy load images where applicable</label></li>
</ul>

<h2 id="win-2-typography">Win #2: Typography</h2>

<p>Typography is a key part of the identity of any company, and plays an important role in helping users parse a web page‚Äôs content more effectively. However, you may not realize the literal weight of every font weight (ha..ha.. ok I‚Äôm sorry about that one). Basically, every weight of every font of every style is another request and a heavier load on the page. For example, these would be six different requests for a single <a href="https://www.myfonts.com/fonts/latinotype/fondue/">typeface</a>:</p>

<p><img src="../images/posts/des-perf/font-weights.jpg" alt="Font Weights" /></p>

<h3 id="typography-optimization-mini-checklist">Typography Optimization Mini-Checklist</h3>

<ul>
  <li><input type="checkbox" /><label>Font audit to group similar styles/font-weights</label></li>
  <li><input type="checkbox" /><label>Consider <a href="http://www.heydonworks.com/article/font-hacking">subsetting</a> Header Typography &amp; individual characters</label></li>
</ul>

<h2 id="win-3-active-waiting">Win #3: Active Waiting</h2>

<p>No matter how much optimization you do, there will still be some delay in load time as assets roll in. This is where design becomes even more important in improving a website‚Äôs performance, and specifically in improving <strong>percieved performance</strong> ‚Äî AKA how fast a user <em>feels</em> the website is loading. Is a lag noticeable?</p>

<blockquote>
  <p>‚ÄúProgress bars are the hold music of the web. They highlight to the user that they‚Äôre waiting‚Äù ‚Äì <a href="https://twitter.com/tkadlec">Tim Kadlec</a></p>
</blockquote>

<p>There is so much you can do to take advantage of this waiting time ‚Äî also known as <strong>active waiting.</strong> Tim Kadlec gave a great <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=S8B7oYsjBtM">talk</a> on this subject where he highlighted some of the behavior that various companies do in this waiting time. For example, Facebook loads up blank divs where the content will go so the user is cued that content is coming, and visually primed to receive it.</p>

<p><img class="right" style="max-width:400px; border: 1px solid lightgray" src="../images/posts/des-perf/fb-waiting.png" alt="Facebook active waiting" /></p>

<p>This is akin to going to a restaurant for dinner. The table is set for food to arrive. We‚Äôre primed to receive it. When we arrive and there is no place setting, if we‚Äôre just sitting there with the menu and nothing else, it feels strange.</p>

<p><a href="http://www.viget.com">Viget</a>, an agency based out of DC, did a <a href="https://www.viget.com/articles/experiments-in-loading-how-long-will-you-wait">study</a> on the customized loading animation vs. generic experiences. They found that ‚ÄúOverall, the branded loading experiences as a group held participants‚Äô on the loading page for longer, and had lower abandon rates than the non-branded, generic experiences.‚Äù</p>

<h3 id="active-waiting-mini-checklist">Active Waiting Mini-Checklist</h3>

<ul>
  <li><input type="checkbox" /><label>Provide a unique waiting experience</label></li>
  <li><input type="checkbox" /><label>Consider UI placeholders</label></li>
</ul>

<p><strong>TL;DR: Image optimization, typography consideration, and active waiting are all ways to improve performance as a designer</strong></p>

